<Document>
<name>Sumatra — Berastagi to Lake Toba</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Sumatra — Berastagi to Lake Toba</h2><p><i>North Sumatra, Indonesia · Medan to Berastagi to Parapat / Samosir Island</i></p><p><b>Through Karo Batak highlands to the world's largest volcanic crater lake — and an island in the middle of it.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>180 km (112 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 3 days with Samosir overnight</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (drier); cool any time at lake altitude (~900 m)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Twisty mountain roads; truck and bus traffic; rain landslides in monsoon; fog on the Karo plateau</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>312</td></tr></table><hr><p>Lake Toba sits in the caldera of one of the largest volcanic eruptions in human prehistory — 74,000 years ago an eruption ejected ~2,800 km³ of material, briefly altered global climate, and may have nearly extinguished the human species (the 'Toba bottleneck' hypothesis). The crater filled with water (now 100 km long, 30 km wide, 500 m deep — the world's largest crater lake) and a resurgent dome inside it became Samosir Island, the size of Singapore. Samosir is the heartland of the Toba Batak people, whose distinctive saddle-roofed houses and Christian-syncretic culture are still strong. Berastagi en route is a Karo Batak highland market town between two active volcanoes (Sibayak and Sinabung; Sinabung erupted seriously 2010–18, displacing thousands). Sipiso-piso waterfall on the lake's north rim drops 120 m in a single thread.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Berastagi</b> — Highland market town at 1,300 m. Strawberry farms, passionfruit, marquisa juice. Sunday farmers' market is one of Sumatra's most colourful.</li><li><b>Mount Sibayak</b> — Active 2,212 m volcano with a rare easy summit — 3 hr return hike to the steaming crater floor. Sulfuric vents, hot streams, can reach the highest viewpoint without technical climbing. Local guides recommended.</li><li><b>Sipiso-piso</b> — 120 m single-thread waterfall on the steep northern rim of the Toba crater. Long view across the lake to Samosir. The 670-step path to the base is steep — bring a torch back up if you stay for sunset.</li><li><b>Parapat</b> — Mainland ferry port for Samosir. Hourly boats to Tuktuk. Old colonial Dutch hill station vibe; mango and durian along the lakeshore.</li><li><b>Tomok</b> — Samosir Island ferry landing. Old Toba Batak tombs and the Sigale-gale puppet — a wooden figure traditionally animated to dance at funerals (now performed for tourists, but still striking).</li><li><b>Tuktuk</b> — Peninsula on the east side of Samosir — the village backpackers fall asleep in for a week. Lakeside guesthouses; warm bathing in the lake; Batak musicians on most evenings.</li><li><b>Pangururan / Mount Pusuk Buhit</b> — West side of Samosir. Hot springs at the base of Mount Pusuk Buhit (1,981 m), the Batak holy mountain — origin of the Batak people in their cosmology. Crossing point to mainland via a small bridge to Sumatra.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
